Now how does White defend the dual threats of ..Rd2 and ..Rd4?} 39. Rc1 Rd2 40.
Rc2 Rxc2 41. Kxc2 Qxc4+ 42. Kd2 Kc6 {and now it's White looking for the draw.})
39. Qxd2 Rxd2 40. Re3 (40. h4 Rd3 41. Rg1 Kb6 {
is much the same - the active rook secures the draw.}) 40... Rxh2 41. Rf3 Kc6
42. Ka2 Rh3 43. Rb3 h4 44. gxh4 Rxh4 45. Rf3 Rh5 {
With the idea of ..Rf5 and ..g5 winning.} 46. Rg3 Rh2 47. Rf3 Rc2 48. Kb3 Rc1
